  "stage": {
    "id": "foundations",
    "stageNumber": 1,
    "title": "Stage 1: Why Attention? From RNNs to Transformers",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "seq2seq",
        "title": "The Problem: RNN Bottlenecks",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- encoder-decoder with hidden states\n- sequential dependency\n- bottleneck problem\n\nRNN seq2seq models compress entire input sequences into one hidden state vector, creating an information bottleneck that hurts long-sequence performance. The Transformer eliminates this by attending directly to all input positions.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "scaled_dot_product_attention",
        "title": "The Core: Scaled Dot-Product Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Q, K, V matrices\n- softmax(QK^T/√d_k)V\n- scaling prevents saturation\n\nWithout scaling, large d_k causes dot products to grow large, pushing softmax into saturation regions with near-zero gradients. Dividing by √d_k keeps gradients healthy.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "positional_encoding",
        "title": "Order Without Recurrence: Positional Encoding",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- sin/cos at different frequencies\n- added to token embeddings\n- enables position awareness\n\nSelf-attention treats input as a set, not a sequence — swapping token positions produces identical attention scores. Sinusoidal positional encodings inject unique position signals so the model knows word order.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-1",
      "question": "Why does the Transformer need positional encoding at all? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "To reduce the vocabulary size",
        "Because self-attention is permutation-invariant and has no built-in notion of position",
        "To speed up training"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Because self-attention is permutation-invariant and has no built-in notion of position",
